  <h2 align="center">Evolution of client-side script:</h2>


  <li>ECMAScript is the 1st client side script used for web applications</li>
    <li>Netscape communications appointed Brendan Eich in 1995 to design a
  client side script for there browser netscape communicator.</li>
  <li>Earlier it was named as "Mocha" and later as "Live Script".</li>
  <li>In the year 1996, Netscape communications and Sun Micro systems
  together announced JavaScript.</li>
  <li>ECMA (European Computer Manufacturer ) Specifies JavaScript
  standandards.</li>
  <li>In the year 1988, MicroSoft started its free browser
  "Internet Explorer" with its OS "Windows 98". The Other free browsers
  were Mosaic, Opera, Safari, etc.</li>
  <li>Netscape communications stopped its browser in the year 1999 and
  handed over JavaScript to ECMA.</li>
  <li>During the years 2000-2001, every browser started its own JavaScript
  to match the market requirements. This leads to browser incompatibility
  issues.</li>
  <li>In the year 2002, W3C took over JavaScript language from ECMA. The
  latest version of JavaScript by W3C is ECMAScript 2017.</li>
  <li>In the year 2006, A library by name "JQuery" was introduced to
  handle the browser incompatibility issues implicitly. However a library
  or script cannot control the application flow. We need a framework
  (Knockout js, Angular js, etc.).</li>
