  <h3>How JavaScript Refers the Elements of HTML?</h3>
  <p>->Html is used to present static DOM and JavaScript is used to manipulate the DOM. <br>JavaScript can refer the HTML elements by using any one of the following methods</p>
  <li><details>
    <summary> Using BOM hierarchy</summary>
    <p style="color: black">In this method HTML elements are accessible by using the document model where every element is defined like an array.<br>
      We can use the index number to access the element. However, changing the position of an element in a page will effect its reference.</p>
    ---><a href="http://htmlbyarun.cf/web_apps/UsingBOM" target="_blank">Example</a>
  </details></li>
  <li><details>
    <summary> Using Name</summary>
    <p style="color: black">Every element in HTML can be defined with a "name" attribute so that we can access the elements by<br> referring to given name.
      However, if the element is a child elementn then we have to access<br> only with the reference of its parent element</p>
    ---><a href="http://htmlbyarun.cf/web_apps/UsingName" target="_blank">Example</a>
  </details></li>
  <li>
  <details>
    <summary> Using ID</summary>
    <p style="color: black">Every element in HTML can be defined with a unique "id". The Javascript document object provides a function "getElementById()" <br>
      Which is used to access any element without following the hierarchy. However, ID have a conflict with CSS id selector.</p>
    ---><a href="http://htmlbyarun.cf/web_apps/UsingID" target="_blank">Example</a>
  </details></li>
  <li>
  <details>
    <summary> Using Tag Name</summary>
    <p style="color: black">The Document object of javascript provides function "getElementsByTagName()", which is used to search for elements <br>
      that are defined by using the given tag name. It returns an array of elements so that we can count the number of elements by using "length".</p>
    ---><a href="http://htmlbyarun.cf/web_apps/UsingTagName" target="_blank">Example</a>
  </details></li>
  <li>
  <details>
    <summary> Using Class name</summary>
    <p style="color: black">To apply Styles we can access all the elements a css class with the help of the function "getElementsByClassName()"</p>
    ---><a href="http://htmlbyarun.cf/web_apps/UsingClass" target="_blank">Example</a>
  </details></li>
  <li>
  <details>
    <summary> Using Reference Name (Different Elements using same name)</summary>
    <p style="color: black">In HTML, various elements can use a common reference name so that among all specified elements<br>
      only one element will be accessed. We can refer all elements by using the function "getElementsByName()".</p>
    ---><a href="http://htmlbyarun.cf/web_apps/UsingReferName" target="_blank">Example</a>
  </details></li>
